    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Game for from two to six players, derived from Halma, which is a checkers-type board game invented about 1880. In Chinese checkers, players attempt to move a number of pieces, usually 10 or 15 marbles, on a board in the shape of a six-pointed star that has holes instead of squares. It was introduced in the United States in the 1930s.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
